 and the timing and circustances of retirement are of growing concern, especially in those cases where employers' demands and imperatives clash with employees' wishes. The contributions in this volume focus upon various measures taken by the state and employers to foster the employment of older workers in Britain, mainland Europe, the US and Japan. The authors address key issues that will influence public policy, exploring what workers over 50 want, the impact of the ageing workforce on employer policies and the implications for governments in promoting and supporting extended working lives. The book is aimed at academics, students, policy makers and other professionals (such as training managers, HR professionals and trade unionists) interested in contemporary issues within social policy, the sociology of ageing, and human resource and diversity management. It wil also be of interest to older workers themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aOlder peoplexEmploymentxForecasting. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh1 aBeatty, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasey, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDanson, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFothergill, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrattan, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffiths, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirsch, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoretto, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoretto, Wendy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMacnicol, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id